  "prompt": "What is the meaning of Urdu compound word \u201cghairat-e-ashiq\u201d?",
  "response": "The Urdu compound word **\u201cghairat-e-ashiq\u201d (\u063a\u06cc\u0631\u062a\u0650 \u0639\u0627\u0634\u0642)** combines two elements:\n\n1. **Ghairat (\u063a\u06cc\u0631\u062a):** This term refers to a sense of honor, dignity, self-respect, or pride. It can also imply jealousy or protectiveness, especially in matters of love or relationships.\n  \n2. **Ashiq (\u0639\u0627\u0634\u0642):** This means \u201clover\u201d or someone deeply in love, often associated with romantic or passionate devotion.\n\nWhen combined, **\u201cghairat-e-ashiq\u201d** translates to **\u201cthe honor of a lover\u201d** or **\u201cthe pride of a lover.\u201d** It conveys the idea of a lover\u2019s deep sense of dignity, self-respect, or protectiveness in the context of their love. It can also imply the passionate and sometimes possessive nature of a lover\u2019s feelings, where they are unwilling to compromise their love or allow any disrespect to it. \n\nIn Urdu poetry and literature, this phrase is often used to describe the intense emotional state of a lover who values their love and honor above all else.",
